I would like to build a VLAN ID management and allocation tool. 

It should be based on Python with support for either/both PostgreSQL or Mongo DB backends. Each table/collection in the database should use use fully-qualified table-relative ID fields (do not use "id" as column name for primary key). For example, the PK column name for the "pool" table would be "pool_id". For Mongo DB, the default ID column of "_id" can be used.

Application should support possibility of configuration of DB via config file for all DB-identifying parameters (host IP/name, port, username, password, etc.).

It should support independent definition of a "customer" with basic attributes of which *ONLY* the customer name is required. Customer names must be globally unique.

It should implement the concept of "pools" of VLAN IDs, which may consist of one or more ranges of VLAN IDs. (It probably makes sense to have "VLAN range" as its own entity type which includes 'start_id' and 'end_id' and is considered an *inclusive* range with a 'type', such as "vlan_pool", "network_scope_reservation", etc. Single-value ranges are allowed by using same value for 'start_id' and 'end_id'.) Each VLAN ID "pool" should capture a 'customer' and 'termination_location' attribute (both text attributes) and the 'termination_location' attribute should be optional. 

System should support concept of a "network scope" which determines the "space" of unique VLAN IDs. All pools within a given "network scope" must have set/collection of unique (non-intersection/non-overlapping) VLAN ID ranges (and, accordingly, all VLAN record allocations from the collection of "pools" in the same "network scope" must be unique). The "network scopes" should allow the "reservation" (prevention of use/exclusion) of VLAN ID ranges, such as 0-1, 2000-2000, 4001-4094.

Each allocated VLAN ID should allow a "reference" (optional) IP address in CIDR format (e.g., 1.2.3.4/24) with proper validation. 

When allocating VLAN ID, the required input should be the 'customer' with optional value of 'termination_location'; if 'termination_location' *IS* specified, then it must be enforced when determining the appropriate VLAN "pool" to use. Likewise, if 'termination_location' is *NOT* specified, then the VLAN ID *must* be allocated from a/the pool with no value for 'termination_location'. 

When allocating VLAN ID, a helper method should be provided which allows input of 'customer' by name and looks up customer_id from name and validates 'termination_location' from list of valid values (TBD) and determines target pool (i.e., pool_id) from this input.

When allocating VLAN IDs from a pool, the "next available" method should be applied according to sequential number among all of the constituent ranges of the "pool". If there is VLAN ID in the pool that has been de-allocated (i.e., is no longer assigned to an "active" allocation), then it should *NOT* be re-used *UNTIL* all of the other available values in constituent range have been used/allocated.

Each VLAN ID allocation should have a unique ID and should reference the pool that it belongs to and have one of the following valid statuses ('assignment_type' attribute) in this explicit lifecycle order:
available --> reserved --> pending --> active --> retired --> quarantined --> available
	- Record can transition reserved --> active without intermediate status of "pending".
	- A record can be created in any of these initial statuses: available, reserved, pending, active
	- If possible (i.e., not too contrived), please allow these status transition rules to be defined in external config file, such as .env_config.

An API/Python method should be provided to allow direct assignment/allocation of VLAN ID using a specified pool, assignment_type (status), and VLAN ID. It should validate that the specified VLAN ID is "available" (not "reserved", "pending" or "assigned"). If a VLAN record exists with that value in "retired" or "quarantined" status, the existing record should be ignored (preserved) and the new assignment allowed.

The VLAN assignment record should contain the following fields/attributes (database IDs can use camel case or underscores in names as per common convention for that platform):
- external_request_id - ID from external system, such as a SAP sys_id
- pool_id - internal ID of the pool it was allocated from
- network_scope_id
- purpose - Textual description of use/purpose of VLAN ID (up to 255 characters)
- customer
- assignment_type - see above regarding "status" - default is "reserved"
- create_date - default is date/time of creation of record (use Unix epoch format without milliseconds)
- update_date - default blank/empty (use Unix epoch format without milliseconds)
	- Set to "now" on *ANY* change/update after record is created.
- activate_date - default blank/empty (use Unix epoch format without milliseconds)
	- Set to "now" when transitioned to assignment_type = "active"
- retire_date - default is empty/blank (use Unix epoch format without milliseconds)
- quarantine_date - default is empty/blank (use Unix epoch format without milliseconds)
	- Set to "now" + configurable number of days when transitioned to assignment_type = "retired". Configured via external configuration file (i.e., .env_config).
- ip_address - optional IP address in CIDR format with validation
- allocation_source - string value indicating how the record was assigned; default value is "automation"

System should provide helper methods for changing the "assignment_type" value of any VLAN ID record by specifying record ID and desired status.

System should provide concept of VLAN ID slots for a given pool to allow better performance when allocating a VLAN ID. After a VLAN ID "slot" is claimed, the system should provide a method to add the claimed "slot" as an assignment and the claimed "slot" should record the assignment ID of the assignment.

